<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>jQuery Animate Example</title>
<script
src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.3.1/jq
uery.min.js"></script>
<script>
$(document).ready(function() {
$("button").click(function() {

var div = $("#box");
div.animate({ left: '100px' }, "slow")
.animate({ fontSize: '3em' }, "slow");
});
});
</script>
<style>
#box {
background: #98bf21;
height: 100px;
width: 200px;
position: absolute; /* Required for 'left' to work */
font-size: 1em;
text-align: center;
line-height: 100px;
color: white;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<button>Start Animation</button>

<p>
By default, all HTML elements have a static position
and cannot be moved.
To manipulate the position, remember to first set the
CSS position property

of the element to relative, fixed, or absolute!
</p>

<div id="box">HELLO</div>

</body>
</html>
